Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
San Francisco – On February 24, Russia's invasion of Ukraine marks the beginning of what could be a third world war capable of destroying our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping had a lengthy meeting on February 4th — a day that marked the beginning of both Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
After the meeting, the two issued a carefully drafted 5,000-word document announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is stronger than any treaty and certainly needs detailed negotiations in advance.
I am shocked that Xi seems to have fully entrusted Putin with the invasion and war in Ukraine.
He believes that the confirmation of his status as China's lifelong ruler this year is merely a formality, and he is confident about it.
After consolidating all power in his hands, Xi meticulously planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin set out to realize his lifelong dream with an incredible brutality.
At 69 years old, Putin feels that if he wants to leave a lasting imprint on Russian history, it is either now or never.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems that he believes the Russian people need a tsar to blindly follow.
This system is in stark contrast to democracy, and this vision distorts the soul of emotionally and sentimentally vulnerable Russian citizens.
In my childhood, I had many interactions with Russian soldiers who had occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them, they will share with you their last loaf of bread.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I called my political charity work.
At first, I established a foundation in my home country, Hungary, and later, I actively participated in the activities that led to the collapse of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev took office in 1985, this disintegration had already begun.
I also established foundations in Russia, and then in each of the republics that broke away afterward.
In Ukraine, and even before it became an independent country, I established a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation there (I closed the foundation in 1989, shortly before the crackdown in Tiananmen Square).
I don't personally know Putin, but I have been closely following his rise to power and am well aware of his cold and ruthless personality.
He reduced Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to rubble, and now he threatens to do the same to Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB officer, but he seems to have changed in recent times.
It seems that he has lost touch with reality because he has formed a fixed notion.
There is no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He had thought that Ukrainian speakers who spoke Russian would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but it turned out they were no different from those who spoke Ukrainian.
Facing what seemed like an overwhelming possibility, Ukrainian civilians still carried out an incredible and brave resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article stating that Russians and Ukrainians are in fact one nation, and that Ukrainians have been misled by neo-Nazi provocateurs.
Because Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church, his argument's first part is not historically unfounded.
But in the contents of Part 2, Putin is the one who was misled.
He should have known the facts more clearly.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely in the Euromaidan protests that erupted in 2014.
The events in 2014 made him very angry.
But when it came to attacking their Ukrainian counterparts as ordered, the Russian military performed poorly.
Corruption rooted in the practice of awarding defense contracts also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But Putin, far from blaming himself, seemed to have lost his mind.
He is determined to punish Ukraine for its opposition, and his actions seem to be unbridled.
He threw the entire Russian army into battle and ignored all rules of engagement, especially indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals have been attacked, and the power grid supplying electricity to the Chernobyl nuclear plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has also been destroyed.
In besieged Mariupol, up to 400,000 people have gone without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
The United States and the EU are both supplying defensive weapons to Ukraine while attempting to purchase MiG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate, which are of Russian manufacture.
These could alter the entire situation.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has already worked a miracle in strengthening Europe’s resolve and unity.
At the same time, it seems that Xi has realized that Putin has been unfaithful.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi reaffirmed that Sino-Russian friendship remains "as solid as a rock," Xi Jinping sent messages of support to French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, expressing his backing for their peacekeeping activities.
To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to exercise maximum restraint in the war.
Whether Putin will accommodate Xi's wishes remains fundamentally uncertain.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
